Basic Cryptography Concepts 

⸻

1. Purpose of Cryptography
	•	Protect information so only intended recipients can understand it
	•	Converts plaintext → ciphertext using an algorithm and key
	•	Security depends on how hard it is to reverse without the key

⸻

2. Caesar Cipher (Substitution Cipher)

Definition
	•	A simple substitution cipher shifting letters by a fixed number

Example
	•	Plaintext: TRY HACK ME
	•	Key: +3
	•	Ciphertext: WUB KDFN PH

Keyspace
	•	25 possible keys (1–25)
	•	0 or 26 → no change

Weakness
	•	Easily broken using brute force
	•	Example:
	•	Ciphertext: YMNX NX FQUMF GWFAT...
	•	Correct key: 5
	•	Result: THIS IS ALPHA BRAVO...

⸻

3. Types of Classical Ciphers

A. Substitution Cipher
	•	Replaces each letter with another
	•	Order remains the same

B. Transposition Cipher
Definition
	•	Rearranges positions of letters without changing them

Process
	1.	Write text in columns
	2.	Rearrange columns using key (e.g., 42351)
	3.	Read row-wise

Key Idea
	•	Letters stay the same, order changes

⸻

4. Brute Force Attack
	•	Try all possible keys
	•	Works when keyspace is small
	•	Example: Caesar cipher easily broken this way

⸻

5. Secure Encryption Requirement
	•	Should be computationally infeasible to break
	•	Based on hard problems
	•	Practical benchmark:
	•	Break in 1 week → insecure
	•	Break in 1 million years → secure

⸻

6. Monoalphabetic Substitution Cipher

Definition
	•	Each letter maps uniquely to another letter

Example Mapping

abcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz
xpatvrzyjhecsdikbfwunqgmol

Keyspace
	•	Extremely large (26! possibilities)

⸻

7. Weakness: Frequency Analysis
	•	English letter frequency:
	•	e → 13%
	•	t → 9.1%
	•	a → 8.2%
	•	Common first letters:
	•	t, a, o

Attack Method
	•	Analyze frequency patterns
	•	Match with known language statistics
	•	Use dictionary words

Example Cipher

Uyv sxd gyi siqvw x sinduxjd pvzjdw...

