8. Key Cryptography Concepts (Overview)

Symmetric Encryption
	•	Same key for encryption & decryption
	•	Example: AES
	•	Fast but key distribution is a problem

Asymmetric Encryption
	•	Public key + private key
	•	Example: RSA
	•	Solves key exchange problem

Diffie-Hellman Key Exchange
	•	Securely shares keys over insecure channels

Hashing
	•	One-way function
	•	Used for passwords, integrity

PKI (Public Key Infrastructure)
	•	Manages keys and certificates
	•	Ensures trust (e.g., HTTPS)

⸻

9. Core Takeaways
	•	Simple ciphers (Caesar, substitution) are not secure
	•	Security depends on:
	•	Key size
	•	Algorithm strength
	•	Modern cryptography relies on:
	•	Mathematical hardness
	•	Computational infeasibility
